root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>246</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon><fr:addr>ct-000N</fr:addr><fr:route>ct-000N.xml</fr:route><fr:title><fr:link
href="ct-000K.xml"
type="local"
addr="ct-000K">Image</fr:link> embedding</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>3</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="frankndrssn.xml"
type="local"
addr="frankndrssn">Frank Tsai</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex>\mathcal { C }</fr:tex> be a category with images. The underlying morphism of the unit <fr:tex>\eta _{f} \colon f \to \mathsf { Img } (f)</fr:tex> is an <fr:link
href="ct-000M.xml"
type="local"
addr="ct-000M">extremal epimorphism</fr:link> for all <fr:tex>f  \in   { \mathcal { C } _{/ B }}</fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    
      
      <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>242</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>3</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="frankndrssn.xml"
type="local"
addr="frankndrssn">Frank Tsai</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>ct-000N</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>
    Since <fr:tex>\mathsf { Img }</fr:tex> maps each morphism <fr:tex>f  \to  f'</fr:tex> in <fr:tex>{ \mathcal { C } _{/ B }}</fr:tex> to the unique morphism <fr:tex>\mathsf { Img } (f)  \to   \mathsf { Img } (f')</fr:tex> in the preorder <fr:tex>\mathsf { Sub } (B)</fr:tex>, it is trivially full. Thus, the unit <fr:tex>\eta _{f}</fr:tex> is a split epimorphism. It remains to show that this epimorphism is extremal.
  </fr:p>
  <fr:p>
    Let <fr:tex>m</fr:tex> be an monomorphism and <fr:tex>g</fr:tex> be a morphism such that <fr:tex>\eta _{f} = mg</fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex>s</fr:tex> be the section to <fr:tex>\eta _{f}</fr:tex>, then <fr:tex>mgs =  \mathsf {id}</fr:tex>. But, this implies that <fr:tex>m</fr:tex> is also a retraction. Thus, it is an monomorphism.
  </fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
    
